<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-oa4xEZg_U1dt02Dm_vhMkw" name="use_case_analysis_uxm,_d5yqVFdaEdqD4uIGCNz_kw" guid="-oa4xEZg_U1dt02Dm_vhMkw" version="7.1.0">
  <sections xmi:id="_Ijk58FhzEdqCqdsoDypiTA" name="Establish Traceability to the User-Experience Model" guid="_Ijk58FhzEdqCqdsoDypiTA">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    During use-case analysis, the user interface can be modeled using boundary &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_analysis_class_DAF7CE03.html&quot; guid=&quot;{1E20603F-A5B8-42D5-BDBC-69DCE9C0FCDB}&quot;>Analysis&#xD;
    Class&lt;/a>es. Since the focus of this task is on the allocation of the requirements (system functionality) to elements&#xD;
    in the solution, in many cases, detailed user-interface modeling is not performed and only one boundary &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_analysis_class_DAF7CE03.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{1E20603F-A5B8-42D5-BDBC-69DCE9C0FCDB}&quot;>Analysis Class&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;is used for each Actor-Use-Case pair (for more&#xD;
    information in identifying Analysis Classes, see &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/guidances/guidelines/analysis_class_7E97273E.html&quot; guid=&quot;2.2738948033145062E-306&quot;>Guideline: Analysis&#xD;
    Class&lt;/a>).&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    However, when the system's user-experience is considered critical to the success of the system, and that&#xD;
    user-experience aspect is new or considered of high risk, a separate&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.ux_model/workproducts/user_experience_model_E11A34D3.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{34EE80D4-460E-494D-BC01-E34D5CB7756A}&quot;>User-Experience Model&lt;/a> is developed. In such cases, the boundary&#xD;
    classes in the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.base_rup/workproducts/rup_analysis_model_76C3B70C.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{98EA224C-36F6-46E6-AB36-2999382B58B3}&quot;>Analysis Model&lt;/a> are considered placeholders for the more detailed user&#xD;
    interface modeling that is captured in the User-Experience Model.&amp;nbsp; Specifically, every boundary class that&#xD;
    represents a user interface should be traced to at least one &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.ux_model/workproducts/user_experience_element_D76CBED9.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{359C3727-8E7C-4C08-BBAA-D428674CB552}&quot;>User-Experience Element&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;in the User-Experience Model.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In those cases, where both an Analysis Model and a User-Experience Model is maintained, it is important to establish&#xD;
    traceability between these models.&amp;nbsp; For more information on this traceability, see &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../extend.ux_model/guidances/guidelines/user_experience_modeling_7EA3D391.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;9.116940284467516E-305&quot;>Guideline: User Experience Modeling&lt;/a> .&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
